example.p:
In  the $4\times 4$ symmetric matrix

C=
\begin{bmatrix}
1 &  0 &  1 &  1\\
0 &  1 &  1 &  1\\
1 &  1 &  1 &  0\\
1 &  1 &  0 &  1
\end{bmatrix}

is shown to have the three eigenvalues $\lambda=3,\,1,\,-1$.  Suppose we wanted a $4\times 4$ matrix that has the three eigenvalues $\lambda=4,\,0,\,-2$.  We can employ  by finding a polynomial that converts $3$ to $4$, $1$ to $0$, and $-1$ to $-2$.  Such a polynomial is called an interpolating polynomial, and in this example we can use

r(x)=\frac{1}{4}x^2+x-\frac{5}{4}

proof.p:
By the definition of the algebraic multiplicity (), we can factor the characteristic polynomial as

\charpoly{A}{x}=c(x-\lambda_1)^{\algmult{A}{\lambda_1}}(x-\lambda_2)^{\algmult{A}{\lambda_2}}(x-\lambda_3)^{\algmult{A}{\lambda_3}}\cdots(x-\lambda_k)^{\algmult{A}{\lambda_k}}

where $c$ is a nonzero constant.  (We could prove that $c=(-1)^{n}$, but we do not need that specificity right now.  See )  The left-hand side is a polynomial of degree $n$ by  and the right-hand side is a polynomial of degree $\sum_{i=1}^{k}\algmult{A}{\lambda_i}$.  So the equality of the polynomials' degrees gives the equality $\sum_{i=1}^{k}\algmult{A}{\lambda_i}=n$.

To show $\geomult{A}{\lambda}\leq\algmult{A}{\lambda}$ is the most involved portion of this proof.  To this end, let $g=\geomult{A}{\lambda}$ and let $\vectorlist{x}{g}$ be a basis for the eigenspace of $\lambda$, $\eigenspace{A}{\lambda}$.  Construct another $n-g$ vectors, $\vectorlist{y}{n-g}$, so that

\set{\vectorlist{x}{g},\,\vectorlist{y}{n-g}}

is a basis of $\complex{n}$.  This can be done by repeated applications of .

This says that $(x-\lambda)$ is a factor of the characteristic polynomial at least $g$ times, so the algebraic multiplicity of $\lambda$ as an eigenvalue of $A$ is greater than or equal to $g$ ().  In other words,

\geomult{A}{\lambda}=g\leq\algmult{A}{\lambda}

as desired.

Let $\vect{x}\neq\zerovector$ be one eigenvector of $A$ for the eigenvalue $\lambda$.   Then by  we know $\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}\neq 0$.  So

\lambda
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\lambda\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\lambda\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{A\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\innerproduct{A\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\innerproduct{\lambda\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}}\conjugate{\lambda}\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{x}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\conjugate{\lambda}
&&\text{}

Let $\vect{x}$ be an eigenvector of $A$ for $\lambda$ and let $\vect{y}$ be an eigenvector of $A$ for a different eigenvalue $\rho$.   So we have $\lambda-\rho\neq 0$.  Then

\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}\left(\lambda-\rho\right)\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}
\left(\lambda\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}-\rho\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}
\left(\innerproduct{\conjugate{\lambda}\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}-\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\rho\vect{y}}\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}
\left(\innerproduct{\lambda\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}-\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{\rho\vect{y}}\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}
\left(\innerproduct{A\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}-\innerproduct{\vect{x}}{A\vect{y}}\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}
\left(\innerproduct{A\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}-\innerproduct{A\vect{x}}{\vect{y}}\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\lambda-\rho}\left(0\right)
&&\text{}\\
&=0

exercise.solution:
Suppose that the vector $\vect{x}
eq\zerovector$ is an eigenvector of $A$ for the two eigenvalues $\lambda$ and $ho$, where $\lambda
eqho$. Then $\lambda-ho
eq 0$, and we also have
\zerovector &=A\vect{x}-A\vect{x}&&	ext{}\ &=\lambda\vect{x}-ho\vect{x}&&	ext{}\ &=(\lambda-ho)\vect{x}&&	ext{}
By , either $\lambda-ho=0$ or $\vect{x}=\zerovector$, which are both contradictions.

Since $\lambda$ is an eigenvalue of a nonsingular matrix, $\lambda\neq 0$ ().  $A$ is invertible (), and so $-\lambda A$ is invertible (). Thus $-\lambda A$ is nonsingular () and $\detname{-\lambda A}\neq 0$ ().

\charpoly{\inverse{A}}{\frac{1}{\lambda}}
&=\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=1\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda A}\detname{\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{\left(-\lambda A\right)\left(\inverse{A}-\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n\right)}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda A\inverse{A}-\left(-\lambda A\right)\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda I_n-\left(-\lambda A\right)\frac{1}{\lambda}I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda I_n+\lambda\frac{1}{\lambda}AI_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda I_n+1AI_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda I_n+AI_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{-\lambda I_n+A}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\detname{A-\lambda I_n}
&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}
\charpoly{A}{\lambda}&&\text{}\\
&=\frac{1}{\detname{-\lambda A}}\,0&&\text{}\\
&=0&&\text{}

So $\frac{1}{\lambda}$ is a root of the characteristic polynomial of $\inverse{A}$ and so is an eigenvalue of $\inverse{A}$.  This proof is due to .
